_source.message:
üëÜüëÜüëÜ

It's good that some states are starting to do something about their voter rolls. Getting rid of ERIC, is just the start.

If we have learnt anything over the last 3 years is that we can NOT be complacent and expect "the state" (any state) to fix things for us.

We need total transparency and grass root teams to take the initiative and lead the effort in keeping voter rolls clean.

We need full voter history of all registered voters, as well as, organized canvassing teams. (Every election should be seen as an opportunity to recruit, learn, and improve canvassing efforts. We need to be able, in time, to canvas a whole county in less than a week. We can make canvassing a lot more effective.)

There is no doubt in my mind that canvassing was, and still is the most effective way of cleaning voter rolls, and goes a long way to keeping the electoral system honest.

This must be a continual and deliberate effort. A civic duty.

KN
